Shows the status of a running HAWQ system.

## <a id="topic1__section2"></a>Synopsis

``` pre
hawq state [-b] [-lÂ logfile_directory] [-v | -q] 
          [-d master_data_directory | --datadir=MASTER\_DIR] [--hawqhome]
hawq state -h | --help
```

## <a id="topic1__section3"></a>Description

The `hawq state` utility displays information about a running HAWQ instance. A HAWQ system is comprised of multiple PostgreSQL database instances (segments) spanning multiple machines, and the `hawq state` utility can provide additional status information, such as:

-   Total segment count.
-   Which segments are down.
-   Master and segment configuration information (hosts, data directories, etc.).
-   The ports used by the system.
-   Whether a standby master is present, and if it is active.

## <a id="topic1__section4"></a>Options

<dt>-b (brief status)  </dt>
<dd>Optional. Display a brief summary of the state of the HAWQ system. This is the default option.</dd>

<dt>-d *master\_data\_directory* | -\\\-datadir=MASTER\_DIR  </dt>
<dd>Status of the master data directory.</dd>


<dt>-\\\-hawqhome=HAWQ\_HOME  </dt>
<dd>Display details of the designated home data directory (usually $GPHOME).</dd>

<dt>-l *logfile\_directory*  </dt>
<dd>Specifies the directory to be used for logfiles. The default is `$GPHOME/hawAdminLogs`.

Log files within the directory are named according to the command being invoked, for example:  hawq\_config\_,log_id>.log, hawq\_init\_<log_id>.log, etc.</dd>

<dt>-q (no screen output)  </dt>
<dd>Optional. Run in quiet mode. Except for warning messages, command output is not displayed on the screen. However, this information is still written to the log file.</dd>

<dt>-v (verbose output)  </dt>
<dd>Optional. Displays error messages and outputs detailed status and progress information.</dd>

<dt>-h | -\\\-help (help)  </dt>
<dd>Displays the online help.</dd>

## <a id="topic1__section6"></a>Examples

Show brief status information of a HAWQ system:

``` shell
$ hawq state -b
```

Change the log directory from `hawqAdminLogs` to `TodaysLogs`.

```shell
$ hawq state -l TodaysLogs
$ ls TodaysLogs
hawq_config_20160707.log  hawq_init_20160707.log   master.initdb
```

